bead.description:
Add a NEW DatabaseRouter alongside the existing TenantRouter. The existing TenantRouter is 510 LOC entangled with the legacy db_name-slug tenancy model — renaming it in place would break many callers. D3 will later unify/retire TenantRouter. This bead's job is to add the new primitive that the new pipeline can use.

## Scope

### 1. New module: crates/axon-server/src/database_router.rs

    //! DatabaseRouter: (tenant_id, database_name) -> storage adapter handle.
    //!
    //! Unlike the legacy TenantRouter which maps a single db_name slug to a
    //! storage handle, DatabaseRouter respects ADR-018's 2-level hierarchy:
    //! a single (tenant, database) pair identifies a unique adapter, and
    //! the same database name under different tenants MUST resolve to
    //! distinct adapters.

    use std::collections::HashMap;
    use std::sync::{Arc, Mutex};

    use axon_core::auth::TenantId;
    use axon_storage::StorageAdapter;

    pub struct DatabaseRouter {
        cache: Mutex<HashMap<(TenantId, String), Arc<dyn StorageAdapter + Send + Sync>>>,
        factory: Arc<dyn DatabaseAdapterFactory + Send + Sync>,
    }

    /// Trait that produces a fresh storage adapter for a given (tenant, database) pair.
    /// In production this provisions a per-database SQLite file or a per-database
    /// Postgres schema. For tests, a MemoryAdapterFactory returns in-memory adapters.
    pub trait DatabaseAdapterFactory {
        fn create_adapter(
            &self,
            tenant_id: TenantId,
            database_name: &str,
        ) -> Result<Arc<dyn StorageAdapter + Send + Sync>, axon_core::error::AxonError>;
    }

    impl DatabaseRouter {
        pub fn new(factory: Arc<dyn DatabaseAdapterFactory + Send + Sync>) -> Self {
            Self { cache: Mutex::new(HashMap::new()), factory }
        }

        /// Resolve a (tenant, database) pair to its storage adapter.
        /// Caches per-pair so repeated resolves return the same Arc<dyn StorageAdapter>.
        pub fn resolve(
            &self,
            tenant_id: TenantId,
            database_name: &str,
        ) -> Result<Arc<dyn StorageAdapter + Send + Sync>, axon_core::error::AxonError> {
            let key = (tenant_id, database_name.to_string());
            let mut cache = self.cache.lock().map_err(|_| axon_core::error::AxonError::Internal("cache mutex poisoned".into()))?;
            if let Some(handle) = cache.get(&key) {
                return Ok(Arc::clone(handle));
            }
            let handle = self.factory.create_adapter(tenant_id, database_name)?;
            cache.insert(key, Arc::clone(&handle));
            Ok(handle)
        }

        /// Drop a cached entry (used when a database is deleted).
        pub fn evict(&self, tenant_id: TenantId, database_name: &str) {
            if let Ok(mut cache) = self.cache.lock() {
                cache.remove(&(tenant_id, database_name.to_string()));
            }
        }
    }

### 2. Provide a MemoryAdapterFactory for tests

    pub struct MemoryAdapterFactory;

    impl DatabaseAdapterFactory for MemoryAdapterFactory {
        fn create_adapter(
            &self,
            _tenant_id: TenantId,
            _database_name: &str,
        ) -> Result<Arc<dyn StorageAdapter + Send + Sync>, axon_core::error::AxonError> {
            Ok(Arc::new(axon_storage::MemoryStorage::new()))
        }
    }

Note: check the actual name of the memory adapter in axon-storage (it may be MemoryStorageAdapter or similar). Use whatever is the canonical public type.

### 3. Tests: crates/axon-server/tests/database_router_test.rs (NEW)

#### resolve_same_pair_returns_same_arc
Create DatabaseRouter with MemoryAdapterFactory. resolve(tenant_a, "orders") twice. Assert both calls return the same Arc pointer (Arc::ptr_eq).

#### different_pairs_return_different_arcs
resolve(tenant_a, "orders") and resolve(tenant_b, "orders") — assert distinct Arcs (not ptr_eq). Same database name under different tenants → different adapters.

#### evict_drops_cache
resolve(tenant_a, "orders") → handle_1. evict(tenant_a, "orders"). resolve(tenant_a, "orders") → handle_2. Assert handle_1 != handle_2 (fresh adapter after eviction).

#### cross_tenant_isolation
resolve(tenant_a, "orders"), write an entity via its adapter. resolve(tenant_b, "orders"), read the same entity ID — assert 404 (not found). Prove data does not leak across the two tenants.

#### factory_error_propagates
Use a FailingFactory that returns Err. Assert resolve returns the same error.

### 4. lib.rs re-exports

Add `pub mod database_router;` and re-export DatabaseRouter + DatabaseAdapterFactory + MemoryAdapterFactory.

## Out of scope

- Actually plumbing DatabaseRouter into the HTTP gateway — that's D3's job. D2 is the primitive + tests.
- Replacing the existing TenantRouter — D3 or later.
- Postgres-backed DatabaseAdapterFactory — memory is enough for this bead; SQLite/Postgres factories are follow-up beads.
- Migration of any existing code from TenantRouter to DatabaseRouter — D3's job.

## Context

- crates/axon-server/src/tenant_router.rs — legacy 510 LOC, DO NOT TOUCH
- crates/axon-storage has MemoryStorageAdapter / SqliteStorageAdapter / PostgresStorageAdapter — DatabaseRouter is factory-parameterized so it does not depend on any specific adapter type
- A1 has the tenant_databases table (validates database existence) — DatabaseRouter itself does NOT validate; the factory is trusted to know what to create. The control plane (C2) is where existence checks live.
- axon-core::auth::TenantId is the typed key; use it verbatim

